Inflection Points

So much of the anxiety across Hollywood these days can be traced to one cau=
se: Streaming. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a terrible business,=E2=80=9D John Mal=
one, the cable TV mogul, told the analyst Craig Moffett earlier this year. =
It may be a frustrating business for Malone and others who got very rich ch=
arging people for cable channels they didn=E2=80=99t watch. But in fact, th=
anks to subscriber gains, the ad tiers, and yes, relentless cost-cutting, a=
ll the major mass-market streamers except Peacock are now profitable=E2=80=
=94with caveats, of course, like Warner Discovery lumping the HBO linear bu=
siness into its direct-to-consumer number. (Amazon and Apple don=E2=80=99t =
provide enough data to judge.) Include Spotify=E2=80=99s recent profitabili=
ty, and it=E2=80=99s a delightfully positive chart, thanks to Owl & Co=E2=
=80=A6.

$(image_link)

So no, streaming was never a terrible business, it just wasn=E2=80=99t near=
ly as good of a business as cable. At least not yet. =E2=80=9CSaying that s=
treaming is a bad business is like saying that retailing is a bad business.=
 Both are misnomers,=E2=80=9D Jason Kilar, the former WarnerMedia C.E.O., t=
weeted a few months ago. =E2=80=9CStrong financial returns can be achieved =
(+ are being achieved) but it requires the right strategy, appropriate reso=
urces, and great execution over long periods of time.=E2=80=9D

That=E2=80=99s a bit rich coming from Kilar, whose window-breaking, walled =
garden strategy at HBO Max during the Covid years ran up huge losses and en=
raged creatives with a day-and-date movie strategy. But in fairness, he nev=
er had the resources needed (AT&T realized only after it decided to go into=
 streaming that it couldn=E2=80=99t spend like Netflix) nor the
time horizon to see how much he could scale. The =E2=80=9Cright=E2=80=9D st=
rategy=E2=80=94the one that Iger and, to a lesser extent, others are seeing=
 success with=E2=80=94seems to be a more modest, narrowly tailored content =
investment, aggressive windowing and third party licensing, and raising pri=
ces for ad-free products to push subscribers to watch commercials. Or, basi=
cally, television. And if there=E2=80=99s one thing Iger knows well, it=E2=
=80=99s television.

