         <!-- REGULAR CONTENT -->
         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s9">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">More importantly, I=
 think we can call another winner in the streaming wars. Netflix, obviously=
, is already one of the three or four video services that will survive this=
 era of digital transition. YouTube is there, too. Spotify, if we count aud=
io. And now, Disney almost certainly will make it. For the first time, the =
company revealed 174 million =E2=80=9CDisney+ Core=E2=80=9D and Hulu subscr=
ibers. (Core excludes India.) Disney+ Core subs were up by 4.4 million. The=
 ad tier is working, with 37 percent of Disney+ subscribers in the U.S. cho=
osing this less expensive but more monetizable option (globally it=E2=80=99=
s 30 percent), allowing Disney to push prices up for the ad-free tier, rais=
ing revenue per subscriber across the board in the process.<br/> <br/>And m=
ost significantly, Disney was confident enough to offer three years of guid=
ance on financials that projected
about $1 billion in profit in streaming for 2025, and a 10 percent profit m=
argin in 2026. If only Chapek had said <i>that</i> on the Oogie Boogie call=
=2E The guidance is likely why the shar=
e price shot up 10 percent today befor=
e closing up about 6 percent. =E2=80=9CIt definitely allays a lot of concer=
ns about the different parts of the business,=E2=80=9D analyst <b>Geetha Ra=
nganathan</b> said on BloombergTV this morning. <br/> <br/>Why the three-ye=
ar projection? <b>Hugh Johnston</b>, the relatively new C.F.O., made the me=
dia rounds today saying it merely stemmed from confidence in the business a=
nd the justification of recent investments in both streaming and the parks.=
 But <b>Rich Greenfield</b>, the Lightshed analyst, noted in a text to me t=
hat =E2=80=9Cthe two biggest investor concerns facing Disney are the impact=
 of Epic on theme parks, and the ramp of sports rights costs on ESPN. By gi=
ving multi-year guidance, they were able to mitigate those concerns.=E2=80=
=9D Rich called the move a =E2=80=9Cbold=E2=80=9D
and =E2=80=9Caggressive=E2=80=9D strategy that =E2=80=9Cclearly speaks to a=
 notable shift in investor strategy under Hugh.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s also =
a way to juice the stagnant stock price <i>now</i> before waiting for those=
 projections to materialize. <br/> <br/>There=E2=80=99s something else unde=
rlying that confidence. It=E2=80=99s becoming clear that Disney, thanks to =
its strong and consistent branding and baked-in fan base, has an advantage =
over others in streaming. Yes, it=E2=80=99s all that I.P. and branded conte=
nt. And it=E2=80=99s the diversified overall business that allows Disney to=
 withstand the decline of TV in a way that others=E2=80=94say, Paramount an=
d Warner Discovery=E2=80=94can=E2=80=99t because their financials are so ti=
ed to linear television. If Disney is showing a 10 percent margin on stream=
ing in a couple years, that profit alone will help offset the ongoing colla=
pse of TV. Then add in parks, products, etc.    <br/> <br/>But it=E2=80=99s=
 also that Disney streaming is <i>branded</i> streaming. Its customers are =
used to following
its content in multiple formats on its journey through the flywheel of full=
y-integrated monetization. So the movies that work in theaters also <i>real=
ly</i> work on Disney streaming (and in Disney parks and Disney cruises and=
 Disney blowout diapers). <i>Inside Out 2</i> and <i>Deadpool and Wolverine=
</i>, both massive grossers in theaters, would be big on any streaming serv=
ice. But they give Disney+ a <i>particularly</i> big and potentially longer=
 boost because they are Disney-branded franchises on a scaled, Disney-brand=
ed service. Longer than, say, <i>Barbie</i> on Max or <i>Top Gun: Maverick<=
/i> on Paramount+. To that end, streaming is just becoming another spoke on=
 the wheel for Disney customers, a spoke that will increase in importance a=
s the TV spoke declines.     <br/></td>
         </tr>
