         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s11">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 26px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">So much of the anxi=
ety across Hollywood these days can be traced to one cause: Streaming. =E2=
=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a terrible business,=E2=80=9D <b>John Malone</b>, the ca=
ble TV mogul, told the analyst <b>Craig Moffett</b> earlier this year. It m=
ay be a <i>frustrating</i> business for Malone and others who got very rich=
 charging people for cable channels they didn=E2=80=99t watch. But in fact,=
 thanks to subscriber gains, the ad tiers, and yes, relentless cost-cutting=
, all the major mass-market streamers except Peacock are now profitable=E2=
=80=94with caveats, of course, like Warner Discovery lumping the HBO linear=
 business into its direct-to-consumer number. (Amazon and Apple don=E2=80=
=99t provide enough data to judge.) Include Spotify=E2=80=99s recent profit=
ability, and it=E2=80=99s a delightfully positive chart, thanks to Owl &amp=
; Co=E2=80=A6.</td>
