         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s12">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">So no, streaming wa=
s never a terrible business, it just wasn=E2=80=99t nearly as good of a bus=
iness as cable. At least not yet. =E2=80=9CSaying that streaming is a bad b=
usiness is like saying that retailing is a bad business. Both are misnomers=
,=E2=80=9D <b>Jason Kilar</b>, the former WarnerMedia C.E.O., tweeted a few=
 months ago. =E2=80=9CStrong financial returns can be achieved (+ are being=
 achieved) but it requires the right strategy, appropriate resources, and g=
reat execution over long periods of time.=E2=80=9D<br/> <br/>That=E2=80=99s=
 a bit rich coming from Kilar, whose window-breaking, walled garden strateg=
y at HBO Max during the Covid years ran up huge losses and enraged creative=
s with a day-and-date movie strategy. But in fairness, he never had the res=
ources needed (AT&amp;T realized only <i>after</i> it decided to go into st=
reaming that it couldn=E2=80=99t spend like Netflix) nor the
time horizon to see how much he could scale. The =E2=80=9Cright=E2=80=9D st=
rategy=E2=80=94the one that Iger and, to a lesser extent, others are seeing=
 success with=E2=80=94seems to be a more modest, narrowly tailored content =
investment, aggressive windowing and third party licensing, and raising pri=
ces for ad-free products to push subscribers to watch commercials. Or, basi=
cally, television. And if there=E2=80=99s one thing Iger knows well, it=E2=
=80=99s television.       <br/></td>
         </tr>
